<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Supplementary description of female.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33A</figureCitation>
) narrow. Body length 3.92 mm. Cephalothoracic shield distinctly longer than wide (1.76 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.36 mm); thoracic zone extending beyond posterior tips of lateral zones. Urosome longer than cephalothoracic shield. Genital complex nearly fusiform, ~ 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (1.07 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.77 mm), incompletely articulated from fourth pedigerous somite, truncate posteriorly. Abdomen 0.61 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.26 mm, unsegmented, elongate, not articulated from genital complex, with wrinkled cuticle at proximal region. Caudal rami (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33B</figureCitation>
) slightly convergent, 2.50 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (195 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
78 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), armed with three large and three small setae; one of small setae positioned ventrally.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figure 33" startId="F33">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Figure 33.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shen &amp; Li" authorityYear="1959" class="Hexanauplia" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Caligus undulatus" order="Caligoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Caligus undulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B</emphasis>
caudal rami, dorsal 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C</emphasis>
sternal furca 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D</emphasis>
distal exopodal segment of leg 1 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E</emphasis>
leg 4. Male 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">F</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A, F</emphasis>
); 0.1 mm (
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B, C, F</emphasis>
); 0.05 mm (
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Sternal furca (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33C</figureCitation>
) narrow; tines gradually narrowed distally, with blunt apex. Distal exopodal segment of leg 1 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33D</figureCitation>
) with three large, pinnate setae on inner margin and four distal armature elements comprising, from outer to inner, claw-like spine 1, smaller claw-like spine 2 bearing accessory process, transparent, aesthetasc-like seta, and long, naked seta. Leg 4 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33E</figureCitation>
) consisting of protopod and two-segmented endopod; protopod with one small seta distally; proximal exopodal segment armed with one spine of 114 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long; distal exopodal segment armed with four spines of 64, 62, 75, and 101 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long, respectively, from proximal to distal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Male.</emphasis>
Body (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 Female A habitus, dorsal B caudal rami, dorsal C sternal furca D distal exopodal segment of leg 1 E leg 4. Male F habitus, dorsal. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A, F); 0.1 mm (B, C, F); 0.05 mm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720753" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">33F</figureCitation>
) smaller than that of female, 3.30 mm long. Cephalic shield 1.75 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.24 mm. Genital complex longer than wide. Abdomen two-segmented; proximal and distal abdominal somites 310 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
250 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
and 360 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
185 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, respectively. Caudal ramus 2.57 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (185 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
72 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shen &amp; Li" authorityYear="1959" class="Hexanauplia" family="Caligidae" genus="Caligus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Caligus undulatus" order="Caligoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Caligus undulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in tropical and warm waters of the world, and has been frequently found from plankton samples. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.12651/JSR.2019.8.4.36" author="Moon, SY" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Species Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="365 - 372" refId="B42" refString="Moon, SY, Park, JS, 2019. Occurrence of sea lice, Caligus undulatus Shen and Li, 1959 (Copepoda: Siphonostomatoida: Caligidae) in plankton samples collected from Korea. Journal of Species Research 8 (4): 365 - 372, DOI: https://doi.org/10.12651/JSR.2019.8.4.36" title="Occurrence of sea lice, Caligus undulatus Shen and Li, 1959 (Copepoda: Siphonostomatoida: Caligidae) in plankton samples collected from Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.12651/JSR.2019.8.4.36" volume="8" year="2019">Moon and Park (2019)</bibRefCitation>
also recorded its occurrence in plankton samples from Korea. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.8.e52271" author="Ohtsuka, S" journalOrPublisher="Records of the South Australian Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B45" refString="Ohtsuka, S, Nawata, M, Nishida, Y, Nitta, M, Hirano, K, Adachi, K, Kondo, Y, Venmathi Maran, BA, Suarez-Morales, E, 2020. Discovery of the fish host of the 'planktonic' caligid Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 (Crustacea: Copepoda: Siphonostomatoida). Biodiversity Data Journal 8: e52271. https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.8.e52271" title="Discovery of the fish host of the ' planktonic' caligid Caligus undulatus Shen &amp; Li, 1959 (Crustacea: Copepoda: Siphonostomatoida). Biodiversity Data Journal 8: e 52271." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.8.e52271" year="2020">Ohtsuka et al. (2020)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the fish 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1854" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clupeidae" genus="Sardinella" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sardinella zunasi" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zunasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Sardinella zunasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Bleeker, 1854) as a host of 
<taxonomicName class="Copepoda" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. undulatus" order="Poecilostomatoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. undulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was the first host record. In the present study, we report 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck &amp; Schlegel" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clupeidae" genus="Konosirus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Konosirus punctatus" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Konosirus punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an additional host record. The fish hosts 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. zunasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="zunasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. zunasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="K." lsidName="K. punctatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">K. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
live on East Asian coasts, sometimes entering bays or brackish waters. It is conceivable that 
<taxonomicName class="Copepoda" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. undulatus" order="Poecilostomatoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. undulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other caligids may detach from the hosts due to the salinity change when the hosts approach brackish waters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A female specimen from Site 11 exhibited a shrunken genital complex with undulated lateral margins as observed in the type material of 
<bibRefCitation author="Shen, CJ" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoological Sinica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="12 - 23" refId="B52" refString="Shen, CJ, Li, HL, 1959. Parasitic copepods from fishes of China, IV. Caligoida. Caligidae (3). Acta Zoological Sinica 11 (1): 12 - 23" title="Parasitic copepods from fishes of China, IV. Caligoida. Caligidae (3)." volume="11" year="1959">Shen and Li (1959)</bibRefCitation>
. This form of the genital complex may occur immediately after oviposition.
</paragraph>
